      More Arrows
   =20
 =20

High on the list of crypto=E2=80=99s most impressive accomplishments is the=
 ability of crypto finance to convince people to=C2=A0lend money, at very h=
igh loan-to-value ratios, against collateral that is somewhere between =E2=
=80=9Cextremely risky=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ctransparently worthless.=E2=80=
=9D We have   talked repeatedly about the time Sam Bankman-Fried said to me=
,=C2=A0on a podcast, that in crypto you can build a box and issue tokens fr=
om the box and =E2=80=9Cput [the] token in a borrow lending protocol and bo=
rrow dollars with it=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cnever, you know, give the dollar=
s back.=E2=80=9D And we have talked about how Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s FTX c=
rypto exchange did more or less exactly that, borrowing billions of dollars=
 of customer money against its stash of made-up tokens and not giving the m=
oney back.
And we have   talked=C2=A0about Kyle Davies, one of the founders of crypto =
trading firm Three Arrows Capital, or 3AC, whose superpower was convincing =
people to lend him hundreds of millions of dollars to do crypto =E2=80=9Car=
bitrage=E2=80=9D trades that were just, like, buying speculative tokens of =
new crypto protocols, holding them for a while and hoping they=E2=80=99d go=
 up. The innovations in 3AC=E2=80=99s business model were:
=09Calling=C2=A0wildly risky venture-type=C2=A0investments=C2=A0=E2=80=9Car=
bitrages,=E2=80=9D so that lenders would assume they were safe, and=09Findi=
ng some really gullible lenders.

As Davies  said in an interview: =E2=80=9CI think one of the last calls we =
did someone lent me high nine figures, almost a billion, off a phone call. =
That was the final one, that was, like, uncollateralized. That=E2=80=99s wh=
ere the system was. People needed to get dollars out the door.=E2=80=9D He =
could help them with that problem. The dollars did not come back=C2=A0in=C2=
=A0the door; 3AC is now bankrupt, and Davies and his cofounder Su Zhu are a=
llegedly=C2=A0not helping its liquidators find whatever money is left.
Based on past results I guess I would say that 3AC=E2=80=99s founders are m=
aybe not that great at=C2=A0trading, but they are world-historically good a=
t getting people to lend money against nonsense, and in crypto in the early=
 2020s that was a=C2=A0valuable skill. They=E2=80=99re  gonna try it again:

The founders of failed hedge fund Three Arrows Capital Ltd. have resurfaced=
 with a $25 million crypto-exchange venture that will let users trade bankr=
uptcy claims from insolvent platforms and funds, including their own.
Open Exchange, or OPNX, was created by Su Zhu and Kyle Davies=E2=80=94who s=
et up Three Arrows together=E2=80=94and the two founders of crypto exchange=
 CoinFLEX. The new platform is expected to launch by the end of this month,=
 Mr. Zhu said. ...
The company=E2=80=99s website said there is a $20 billion market of crypto =
claimants, and the exchange will allow creditors to convert their claims in=
to cryptocurrencies to use them as margin collateral for crypto futures tra=
ding. Claims against Three Arrows Capital are among those that can be trade=
d on the new exchange, in addition to claims against FTX, Genesis Global Ca=
pital, Celsius Network LLC and others, OPNX said.

=E2=80=9CUse them as margin collateral for crypto futures trading=E2=80=9D!=
 We have   discussed this plan before, and I love it. Like:
=093AC borrows a lot of money to buy tokens, posting the tokens as collater=
al for the loans.=09The tokens turn out to be worthless, 3AC doesn=E2=80=99=
t pay back the loans=C2=A0and goes bankrupt.=093AC helps the lenders turn t=
he loans into new tokens, listed on its own bankruptcy token exchange.=09Tr=
aders on the exchange borrow a lot of money to buy the new tokens, posting =
the new tokens as collateral for the loans.=09If you were to write =E2=80=
=9Cgo to Step 2,=E2=80=9D who would blame you?

It is so pure? We   talked yesterday about US regulators=E2=80=99 current=
=C2=A0crackdown on various crypto projects. Here is   a Bloomberg News stor=
y about how US regulators=C2=A0=E2=80=9Ccould push the industry to the frin=
ges of finance,=E2=80=9D cutting crypto off from banking services and US re=
tail money. (And  here is a Wall Street Journal story about how =E2=80=9Cth=
ere=E2=80=99s a crypto carpet bombing going on right now=E2=80=9D among US =
regulators.) One possible path for crypto is =E2=80=94=C2=A0was? =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0that it would become increasingly mainstream, that it would attract i=
nstitutional money and become well integrated with the broader financial sy=
stem. That path seems increasingly inaccessible. Another possible path is f=
or crypto to become increasingly self-referential, to retreat from the real=
 world and the broader financial system and just become a way to trade abst=
ract claims on itself. =E2=80=9CCrypto is a way to trade tokens representin=
g previous crypto failures=E2=80=9D is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0something? Some sort =
of business model? Very funny?
One thing that I think about a lot is that the victims of frauds are promis=
ing targets for subsequent frauds. If you get a list of the emails of peopl=
e who got tricked into a Ponzi scheme, and you send them a poorly spelled e=
mail saying =E2=80=9CI am a brilliant secret=C2=A0private investigator=C2=
=A0and I can get you back all the money you lost in that Ponzi scheme, just=
 wire a $10,000 deposit to my account and I=E2=80=99ll get right on that,=
=E2=80=9D you can make a lot of money,
  [1]
 because these are people who are temperamentally disposed to being scammed=
, and because nobody ever learns anything from experience. The founders of =
3AC have lost a lot of money, which apparently=C2=A0means that they are=C2=
=A0well positioned to start another business. Few people in crypto were=C2=
=A0better at getting people to trust them than Davies and Zhu, and few peop=
le in the world were better at=C2=A0trusting Davies and Zhu=C2=A0than the p=
eople who now have bankruptcy claims against 3AC, so they might as well get=
 back together.

