   =20
      Oh Elon
   =20
 =20

Remember last year when Elon Musk was going around   pretending that Twitte=
r Inc. was   doing a whole assortment of fraud, hoping that some of it woul=
d stick so that he could get out of his deal to buy Twitter? That was annoy=
ing. It did not go well, for him, and he eventually dropped it and bought T=
witter at the price he had originally agreed to. But if you go around telli=
ng everyone that a US public company is committing all sorts of fraud, then=
 some securities lawyers are definitely going to sue the company for that a=
lleged fraud, and they definitely did.
And now Musk owns the company and has to defend that fraud suit =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0hard, given that he has previously claimed to agree with it! =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0or else pay damages =E2=80=94=C2=A0unfair, since, in the somewhat =
imaginary world in which Twitter was doing a bunch of fraud, Musk is the bi=
ggest=C2=A0victim=C2=A0of that fraud! On the fraud theory of Twitter, Twitt=
er was doing a bunch of fraud that propped up its stock price, and then Mus=
k agreed to buy it at a premium to that inflated price, and then the fraud =
was disclosed, and then Musk grumbled but bought it anyway at that inflated=
 premium price, and now the shareholders who=C2=A0sold=C2=A0get to sue=C2=
=A0him=C2=A0for more money? Seems very unfair, and yet somehow hilariously =
deserved.
Anyway yesterday the plaintiffs in the federal securities fraud case agains=
t Twitter filed their  amended complaint. It plays all the hits that you mi=
ght remember from last year =E2=80=94=C2=A0mDAUs!   Mudge! =E2=80=94=C2=A0a=
nd I am absolutely not going to read or write about any of the fraud claims=
. The weird part is figuring out how the shareholders were, allegedly, harm=
ed. Let=E2=80=99s say that Twitter was doing assorted frauds that inflated =
its price: Musk still bought it at that inflated price. So how did sharehol=
ders get hurt? From the complaint:

In April 2022, Twitter=E2=80=99s Board accepted a buyout offer from Elon Mu=
sk (=E2=80=9CMusk=E2=80=9D). Yet the deal quickly soured.
On May 13, 2022, before the market opened, Musk tweeted out concerns about =
Twitter=E2=80=99s representations concerning the number of bots. Twitter=E2=
=80=99s stock price fell 9.7% that day, falling another 8.2% over the next =
day as Musk continued to tweet his concerns.
On July 7, 2022, the Washington Post reported that Musk had stopped engagin=
g in certain discussions around the deal. Twitter=E2=80=99s stock price fel=
l 5.1%.
Then on July 8, 2022, Twitter publicly filed with the SEC a letter from Mus=
k terminating the deal, citing misrepresentations concerning the number of =
bots. Twitter=E2=80=99s stock price plunged 11.3%.

And:

On the weekend of May 14 and 15, 2022, Musk continued to tweet about the pr=
evalence of fake or spam accounts on Twitter. On May 14, Musk tweeted that =
his =E2=80=9Cteam will do a random sample of 100 followers of @twitter=E2=
=80=9D to determine how many were fake or spam accounts, and that =E2=80=9C=
I picked 100 as the sample size because that is what Twitter uses to calcul=
ate <5% fake/spam/duplicate.=E2=80=9D Later that same day, Musk tweeted: =
=E2=80=9CTwitter legal just called to complain that I violated their NDA by=
 revealing the bot check sample size is 100! This actually happened.=E2=80=
=9D On May 15 he said in two tweets that =E2=80=9CI have yet to see *any* a=
nalysis that has fake/spam/duplicates at 5%=E2=80=9D. Further, during the t=
rading day on May 16, 2022, in response to tweets by Defendant Agrawal conc=
erning the prevalence of fake or spam accounts, Musk asked on Twitter =E2=
=80=9CSo how do=C2=A0advertisers know what they=E2=80=99re getting for thei=
r money? This is fundamental to the financial health of Twitter.=E2=80=9D
In response to this news, the price of Twitter=E2=80=99s common stock fell =
8.18%, or $3.33, from a closing price of $40.72 on May 13, 2022, to close a=
t $37.39 on the next trading day, May 16, 2022.

So what? Eventually Musk bought Twitter for $54.20 per share, as agreed. Bu=
t I think what those passages mean=C2=A0is that if you bought Twitter stock=
 after Musk agreed to buy Twitter, and then you sold it after Musk tweeted =
it was a fraud and the stock dropped, you lost money and are entitled to co=
mpensation from Twitter. They=E2=80=99re suing Musk for tweeting that Twitt=
er was a fraud. Serves him right, really.
In other news, here is a story about Musk allegedly  firing an engineer who=
 told him that people don=E2=80=99t read his tweets because they=E2=80=99ve=
 lost interest, and here is  another story about how Twitter is allegedly i=
njecting Musk=E2=80=99s tweets into users=E2=80=99 timelines. Look, I mean,=
 as a Twitter user, I do not love that Twitter is now the Elon Musk Show al=
l the time. But, as a Twitter user,=C2=A0he=C2=A0clearly loves that, and he=
 does own the company! He can do what he wants! When he first bought shares=
 in Twitter,   I imagined a dialogue between Musk (as a big but outside sha=
reholder and a devoted user of Twitter) and then-Chief Executive Officer Pa=
rag Agrawal:

Elon Musk: Make the font bigger when I tweet.
Agrawal: What?=C2=A0
Musk: I am your biggest shareholder, I want the font on my tweets to be big=
ger than the font on everyone else=E2=80=99s tweets.
Agrawal: That=E2=80=99s not really how we=E2=80=94
Musk: And I want 290 characters. Again, just for me.
Agrawal: =E2=80=A6
Musk: And it should play a little sound when I tweet so everyone knows.

Then he bought the company and fired Agrawal and everyone else who objected=
 to this plan, so here we are I guess.

