   =20
      Mark to market
   =20
 =20

Last September the market for UK government bonds broke down briefly due to=
 weird dynamics involving pension funds and liability-driven investment. Ba=
sically LDI fund managers ran large leveraged positions in UK gilts on beha=
lf of pension funds, gilt rates went up, those pension funds faced collater=
al calls and had to dump gilts, that drove rates up more, etc.; sort of a s=
tandard unwind of a leveraged trade. We  talked about it at the time. Event=
ually the Bank of England stepped in, announcing that it would buy a bunch =
of gilts to keep yields down, and things were fine again. Bloomberg data te=
lls me that 10-year gilts traded at about 3.82% on Sept. 23, got up to 4.24=
% on Sept. 26 and 4.50% on Sept. 27, and then fell to 4.01% after the BoE a=
nnounced its plan.
Here is a Financial Times story about how one LDI manager, Insight Investme=
nts, decided not to mark its fund to market on Sept. 27, because the market=
 was too ugly:

One of the UK pension industry=E2=80=99s biggest asset managers abandoned m=
ark-to-market pricing on funds reeling from the country=E2=80=99s governmen=
t bond crisis last year, instead choosing higher values that presented a ro=
sier picture of its position. ...
A vicious cycle developed in which drops in gilt prices forced LDI managers=
 to sell more gilts to raise cash, because their funds used leverage. Most =
LDI managers also marked down the value of their funds each day in line wit=
h plunging gilt prices.
But on the day the Bank of England stepped in with a rescue scheme, Insight=
 disregarded market prices and set its own, pushing its funds=E2=80=99 net =
asset values per share higher, in some cases markedly. =E2=80=A6
=E2=80=9CMarkets were dysfunctional,=E2=80=9D Insight told the FT. =E2=80=
=9CIn such circumstances, the fund board has discretion to apply a fair val=
ue adjustment to market prices. A decision of this nature is made in the be=
st interest of all shareholders in a fund.=E2=80=9D
Industry experts say the price adjustment prevented Insight from making dem=
ands for cash of its clients. =E2=80=9CNAVs should tell you asset values,=
=E2=80=9D said one. =E2=80=9CThe injured party is trust in the system.=E2=
=80=9D

Yes, well. We  talk sometimes around here about the value of not marking to=
 market: Investors will pay premiums, in various contexts, for the service =
of=C2=A0not knowing what their investments are worth, particularly when the=
y are going down. Here Insight=E2=80=99s clients do seem to have benefited =
from not being told what their investments were worth that day, even if =E2=
=80=9Ctrust in the system=E2=80=9D did not.=C2=A0
That said I do want to say something about the timing here. The way this wo=
rked is that Insight provided its Sept. 27 marks at midday on Sept. 28:

Insight=E2=80=99s actions on September 28 illustrate how =E2=80=9Ctough=E2=
=80=9D it was. By that morning, LDI funds were starting to crack. The BoE l=
ater described this as a period when market participants were =E2=80=9Cshou=
ting on the phone=E2=80=9D for help. Insight had just hours left before it =
reported the value on its funds for September 27 =E2=80=94 a typically humd=
rum daily process that involves scraping data on the previous day=E2=80=99s=
 gilts prices and reporting the numbers each afternoon.
Marking the funds to market at September 27 rates, close to the lowest poin=
t in the crisis, would have generated a grim result. Instead, for that one =
day, Insight took another path. After the BoE announced its targeted bond-b=
uying rescue scheme at 11am on September 28, which instantly pushed gilts p=
rices higher, it gathered its five-person fund board, which comprised three=
 independent members and others from BNY and Insight. They decided to mark =
the books for September 27 higher by disregarding that day=E2=80=99s gilt m=
oves and marking to market around prices that had prevailed in the middle o=
f September 26.

By the time they were marking the books for Sept. 27, it was Sept. 28, and =
the market had=C2=A0already=C2=A0recovered. It is one thing to sit there at=
 the close on Sept. 27, look at a horrific drop in your asset values, and s=
ay =E2=80=9Cahhh, this is just a blip, this isn=E2=80=99t real, everything =
is fine, let=E2=80=99s report a higher value.=E2=80=9D That sounds like wis=
hful thinking! But it is something else to sit there at noon on Sept. 28, l=
ook at yesterday=E2=80=99s horrific drop in your asset values=C2=A0and toda=
y=E2=80=99s recovery, and say =E2=80=9Cahhh, yesterday=E2=80=99s drop was j=
ust a blip, it wasn=E2=80=99t real, everything turned out fine, let=E2=80=
=99s report a higher value for yesterday.=E2=80=9D It seems a little bit mo=
re justifiable to smooth out volatility in returns when you already know wh=
at happened next, and in fact the volatility was smoothed out in the real w=
orld.

