y mainstream, that it would attract institutional money and become well int=
egrated with the broader financial system. That path seems increasingly ina=
ccessible. Another possible path is for crypto to become increasingly self-=
referential, to retreat from the real world and the broader financial syste=
m and just become a way to trade abstract claims on itself. =E2=80=9CCrypto=
 is a way to trade tokens representing previous crypto failures=E2=80=9D is=
 =E2=80=A6=C2=A0something? Some sort of business model? Very funny?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing that I think about a lot is that the=
 victims of frauds are promising targets for subsequent frauds. If you get =
a list of the emails of people who got tricked into a Ponzi scheme, and you=
 send them a poorly spelled email saying =E2=80=9CI am a brilliant secret=
=C2=A0private investigator=C2=A0and I can get you back all the money you lo=
st in that Ponzi scheme, just wire a $10,000 deposit to my account and I=E2=
=80=99ll get right on that,=E2=80=9D you can make a lot of money,<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !=
important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> because these are people who are temperamentally disposed to being sca=
mmed, and because nobody ever learns anything from experience. The founders=
 of 3AC have lost a lot of money, which apparently=C2=A0means that they are=
=C2=A0well positioned to start another business. Few people in crypto were=
=C2=A0better at getting people to trust them than Davies and Zhu, and few p=
eople in the world were better at=C2=A0<em>trusting Davies and Zhu=C2=A0</e=
m>than the people who now have bankruptcy claims against 3AC, so they might=
 as well get back together.</p>
