<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last September the market for UK government bo=
nds broke down briefly due to weird dynamics involving pension funds and li=
ability-driven investment. Basically LDI fund managers ran large leveraged =
positions in UK gilts on behalf of pension funds, gilt rates went up, those=
 pension funds faced collateral calls and had to dump gilts, that drove rat=
es up more, etc.; sort of a standard unwind of a leveraged trade. We <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30552542.269805/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDktMjkvdWstcGVuc2l=
vbnMtZ290LW1hcmdpbi1jYWxscz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMjE0MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaX=
VtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAyMTQmdXRtX2NhbXBha=
WduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe079ec1e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked about=
 it at the time</a>. Eventually the Bank of England stepped in, announcing =
that it would buy a bunch of gilts to keep yields down, and things were fin=
e again. Bloomberg data tells me that 10-year gilts traded at about 3.82% o=
n Sept. 23, got up to 4.24% on Sept. 26 and 4.50% on Sept. 27, and then fel=
l to 4.01% after the BoE announced its plan.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/30552542.269805/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvOW=
EwZDQxY2UtYTAyOS00Y2MyLWEwMTMtZGViNDA0OTBkYWIy/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1e1=
f69eb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;">Financial Times story</a> about how one LDI manager, Insight=
 Investments, decided not to mark its fund to market on Sept. 27, because t=
he market was too ugly:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One of the UK pension industry=E2=80=99s bigge=
st asset managers abandoned mark-to-market pricing on funds reeling from th=
e country=E2=80=99s government bond crisis last year, instead choosing high=
er values that presented a rosier picture of its position. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A vicious cycle developed in which drops in gi=
lt prices forced LDI managers to sell more gilts to raise cash, because the=
ir funds used leverage. Most LDI managers also marked down the value of the=
ir funds each day in line with plunging gilt prices.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But on the day the Bank of England stepped in =
with a rescue scheme, Insight disregarded market prices and set its own, pu=
shing its funds=E2=80=99 net asset values per share higher, in some cases m=
arkedly. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CMarkets were dysfunctional,=E2=80=9D =
Insight told the FT. =E2=80=9CIn such circumstances, the fund board has dis=
cretion to apply a fair value adjustment to market prices. A decision of th=
is nature is made in the best interest of all shareholders in a fund.=E2=80=
=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Industry experts say the price adjustment prev=
ented Insight from making demands for cash of its clients. =E2=80=9CNAVs sh=
ould tell you asset values,=E2=80=9D said one. =E2=80=9CThe injured party i=
s trust in the system.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes, well. We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/30552542.269805/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS=
9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMDQvcHJpdmF0ZS1tYXJrZXRzLWRvbi10LWxpa2Utd=
G8tZ28tZG93bj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMjE0MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0=
bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAyMTQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R=
1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcd0bead0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> talk sometimes</a> around =
here about the value of not marking to market: Investors will pay premiums,=
 in various contexts, for the service of=C2=A0<em>not knowing what their in=
vestments are worth</em>, particularly when they are going down. Here Insig=
ht=E2=80=99s clients do seem to have benefited from not being told what the=
ir investments were worth that day, even if =E2=80=9Ctrust in the system=E2=
=80=9D did not.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That said I do want to say something about the=
 timing here. The way this worked is that Insight provided its Sept. 27 mar=
ks at midday on Sept. 28:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Insight=E2=80=99s actions on September 28 illu=
strate how =E2=80=9Ctough=E2=80=9D it was. By that morning, LDI funds were =
starting to crack. The BoE later described this as a period when market par=
ticipants were =E2=80=9Cshouting on the phone=E2=80=9D for help. Insight ha=
d just hours left before it reported the value on its funds for September 2=
7 =E2=80=94 a typically humdrum daily process that involves scraping data o=
n the previous day=E2=80=99s gilts prices and reporting the numbers each af=
ternoon.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Marking the funds to market at September 27 ra=
tes, close to the lowest point in the crisis, would have generated a grim r=
esult. Instead, for that one day, Insight took another path. After the BoE =
announced its targeted bond-buying rescue scheme at 11am on September 28, w=
hich instantly pushed gilts prices higher, it gathered its five-person fund=
 board, which comprised three independent members and others from BNY and I=
nsight. They decided to mark the books for September 27 higher by disregard=
ing that day=E2=80=99s gilt moves and marking to market around prices that =
had prevailed in the middle of September 26.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By the time they were marking the books for Se=
pt. 27, it was Sept. 28, and the market had=C2=A0<em>already=C2=A0</em>reco=
vered. It is one thing to sit there at the close on Sept. 27, look at a hor=
rific drop in your asset values, and say =E2=80=9Cahhh, this is just a blip=
, this isn=E2=80=99t real, everything is fine, let=E2=80=99s report a highe=
r value.=E2=80=9D That sounds like wishful thinking! But it is something el=
se to sit there at noon on Sept. 28, look at yesterday=E2=80=99s horrific d=
rop in your asset values=C2=A0<em>and today=E2=80=99s recovery</em>, and sa=
y =E2=80=9Cahhh, yesterday=E2=80=99s drop was just a blip, it wasn=E2=80=99=
t real, everything turned out fine, let=E2=80=99s report a higher value for=
 yesterday.=E2=80=9D It seems a little bit more justifiable to smooth out v=
olatility in returns when you already know what happened next, and in fact =
the volatility was smoothed out in the real world.</p>
